, "mention": "retinaldehyde dehydrogenase ALDH1A", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9830598831176758, "span": {"begin": 471, "end": 505}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:216"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "ALDH1A1", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9909257888793945, "span": {"begin": 507, "end": 514}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:8854"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "ALDH1A2", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9727233052253723, "span": {"begin": 516, "end": 523}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:220"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "ALDH1A3", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9673865437507629, "span": {"begin": 525, "end": 532}}, {"id": ["mesh:D012172"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "retinaldehyde", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9995623230934143, "span": {"begin": 546, "end": 559}}, {"id": ["mesh:D014212"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "atRA", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.989666223526001, "span": {"begin": 664, "end": 668}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:8854"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "ALDH1A2", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9911002516746521, "span": {"begin": 674, "end": 681}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:8854"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "ALDH1A2", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9215345978736877, "span": {"begin": 765, "end": 772}}, {"id": ["mesh:D014212"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "atRA", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9678462743759155, "span": {"begin": 806, "end": 810}}], "text": "All-trans retinoic acid (atRA) is the active metabolite of vitamin A in developing mammals and its physiological levels is tightly regulated by enzymatic pathways. This KER is particularly relevant for mammalian embryogenesis/fetal development stages.   atRA is synthesized from dietary vitamin A (retinol) by a two-step oxidation pathway (Chatzi et al, 2013; Kedishvili, 2016): 1) retinol dehydrogenase (RDH10) metabolizes retinol to retinaldehyde (reversible step), 2) retinaldehyde dehydrogenase ALDH1A (ALDH1A1, ALDH1A2, ALDH1A3) metabolizes retinaldehyde to RA (irreversible step). All three isoenzymes can carry out the second (irreversible step) to produce atRA, but ALDH1A2 is the most active form during development (Kedishvili, 2016). Thus, inhibition of ALDH1A2 during development will decrease atRA concentrations.", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 15:35:07 +0000 2026"}